  "What is a 'radical'?": "",
  "A type of fraction": "",
  "The symbol √ that indicates a root of a number": "",
  "An exponent that is negative": "",
  "A polynomial with three terms": "",
  "A radical is the symbol √ (or higher-index roots like ∛) used to indicate a root. The expression under the radical sign is called the radicand.": "",
  "What is a 'radicand'?": "",
  "The simplified answer": "",
  "The number or expression under the radical sign": "",
  "The number in front of the radical sign": "",
  "The index of the radical": "",
  "The radicand is the number or expression inside (under) the radical symbol. For example, in √48, the radicand is 48.": "",
  "What is a 'perfect square'?": "",
  "A number greater than 100": "",
  "A number that ends in zero": "",
  "A number whose square root is a whole number, like 4, 9, 16, 25": "",
  "Any even number": "",
  "A perfect square is a number that results from squaring a whole number: 1, 4, 9, 16, 25, 36, 49, 64, 81, 100, etc.": "",
  "What does 'simplest radical form' mean?": "",
  "The expression contains no variables": "",
  "The radical equals a whole number": "",
  "No perfect square factors remain under the radical and no radicals appear in a denominator": "",
  "The radical has the smallest possible index": "",
  "A radical is in simplest form when: (1) no perfect square factors remain under the radical, (2) no fractions are under the radical, and (3) no radicals appear in the denominator.": "",
  "What does 'rationalize the denominator' mean?": "",
  "Simplify the numerator only": "",
  "Convert the radical to a decimal": "",
  "Remove all fractions from the expression": "",
  "Eliminate the radical from the denominator by multiplying top and bottom by an appropriate radical": "",
  "Rationalizing the denominator means rewriting the expression so no radical appears in the denominator. Multiply numerator and denominator by the same radical to eliminate it.": "",
  "What is the 'product property of radicals'?": "",
  "√(a/b) = a/√b": "",
  "√(a · b) = √a · √b for non-negative a and b": "",
  "√(a + b) = √a + √b": "",
  "√(a − b) = √a − √b": "",
  "The product property states √(a · b) = √a · √b when a ≥ 0 and b ≥ 0. This is the key property used to simplify radicals by separating perfect square factors.": "",
  "What is the 'quotient property of radicals'?": "",
  "√(a/b) = √a − √b": "",
  "√(a/b) = √a / √b for positive b": "",
  "√(a/b) = a / √b": "",
  "√(a/b) = √a + √b": "",
  "The quotient property states √(a/b) = √a / √b when a ≥ 0 and b > 0. This lets you simplify radicals of fractions by taking the root of numerator and denominator separately.": "",
  "What is the 'index' of a radical?": "",
  "The number that tells which root to take (2 for square root, 3 for cube root)": "",
  "The coefficient in front of the radical": "",
  "The number inside the radical": "",
  "The exponent of the variable": "",
  "The index is the small number written in the crook of the radical sign (e.g., ∛ has index 3). For square roots, the index is 2 and is usually not written.": "",
  "What is a 'perfect square factor'?": "",
  "Any factor of the radicand": "",
  "The radicand divided by 2": "",
  "The largest prime factor": "",
  "A factor of the radicand that is itself a perfect square": "",
  "A perfect square factor is a factor of the radicand that is a perfect square. For example, in √72, the perfect square factor 36 (since 72 = 36 × 2) lets us simplify to 6√2.": "",
  "What is a 'conjugate' in the context of rationalizing denominators?": "",
  "The reciprocal of the denominator": "",
  "The numerator flipped upside down": "",
  "The square of the denominator": "",
  "The expression formed by changing the sign between two terms, such as (a + √b) and (a − √b)": "",
  "The conjugate of (a + √b) is (a − √b). Multiplying by the conjugate eliminates the radical because (a + √b)(a − √b) = a² − b.": "",
